  "description": "SNES .srm files are raw dumps of the battery-backed SRAM from a Super Nintendo cartridge. They have no header, magic bytes, or metadata — the file contains pure SRAM data as it existed on the cartridge chip. Emulators (snes9x, bsnes, RetroArch) save and load .srm files with the same base filename as the ROM. Common sizes: 2KB (0x800) for most RPGs (Final Fantasy VI, Chrono Trigger), 8KB (0x2000) for some titles, and 32KB (0x8000) for special cartridges. The SRAM layout is game-specific — each game stores its save data in its own format within the SRAM space. Some cartridges use RTC (real-time clock) data appended after the SRAM (e.g., Harvest Moon). The SNES CPU addresses SRAM in banks $70-$7D at $7000-$7FFF (LoROM) or banks $20-$3F/$A0-$BF at $6000-$7FFF (HiROM). Emulator .srm files mirror this layout directly.",
